  <h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Temperature Precision Matters More for Champagne</strong> - Serve Champagne at 43-46°F and Prosecco slightly warmer at 46-50°F. Champagne's complex autolytic flavors (brioche, nuts) emerge better at the cooler temperature, while Prosecco's fresh fruit character shines when not over-chilled. Use an ice bucket with half ice, half water for Champagne; a regular refrigerator chill suffices for Prosecco.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Glassware Choice Reveals Different Aromatics</strong> - Use tulip-shaped flutes for Champagne to concentrate its delicate mousse and showcase secondary fermentation aromas. For Prosecco, slightly wider bowls work better to capture the primary fruit aromatics from the Charmat method. Avoid coupes for both, but especially for Champagne, as they dissipate the precious bubbles too quickly.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Never Decant Either, But Handle Storage Differently</strong> - Neither Champagne nor Prosecco should be decanted as this destroys their effervescence. However, Champagne can be stored upright for short periods without harm due to its robust mousse, while Prosecco should always remain horizontal to keep the cork moist and prevent premature oxidation of its more delicate structure.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Age Assessment Through Bubble Analysis</strong> - Champagne's bubbles become finer and more persistent with age due to riddling and longer lees contact—look for a steady, fine mousse. Prosecco bubbles are naturally larger and more aggressive when fresh; if they're weak or dissipate quickly, the wine is past its prime. Vintage Champagne can improve for decades, while even the finest Prosecco should be consumed within 2-3 years.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Disgorgement Dates Trump Vintage Dates for Champagne</strong> - For Champagne, seek the disgorgement date (often printed as a small code) rather than just the vintage—this tells you when the wine was actually finished. A 2015 Champagne disgorged in 2023 will taste fresher than one disgorged in 2020. Prosecco doesn't undergo disgorgement, so focus on the harvest date and choose the most recent available.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Pressure Differences Affect Opening Technique</strong> - Champagne contains 6 atmospheres of pressure versus Prosecco's 3-4 atmospheres. Open Champagne by holding the cork steady and twisting the bottle—the higher pressure requires more control. Prosecco can be opened more casually, but still avoid the dramatic pop that wastes precious wine and aromatics.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Dosage Levels Require Different Food Pairing Strategies</strong> - Champagne's dosage (added sugar) ranges from Brut Nature (0g/L) to Doux (50g/L), affecting food compatibility. Prosecco is typically Brut (under 12g/L) with consistent sweetness levels. Match bone-dry Extra Brut Champagne with oysters, while Prosecco's slight residual sugar pairs beautifully with prosciutto and Asian cuisine that would overpower delicate Champagne.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Seasonal Timing Optimizes Each Style's Strengths</strong> - Serve aged Champagne (5+ years) during cooler months when its complex, yeasty flavors complement heartier fare and contemplative sipping. Reserve fresh Prosecco for warm weather and casual occasions when its bright acidity and immediate fruit appeal provide refreshing satisfaction without the ceremony that fine Champagne deserves.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which is better value: Champagne or Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Prosecco offers significantly better value for everyday drinking, with quality bottles starting around $12-20 compared to entry-level Champagne at $40-50. However, Champagne provides unmatched complexity and aging potential for special occasions. For regular consumption, a good Prosecco di Valdobbiadene DOCG delivers exceptional quality-to-price ratio, while Champagne excels when you want maximum prestige and sophistication.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you tell the difference between Champagne and Prosecco when served blind?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, experienced tasters can distinguish them by key characteristics: Champagne typically shows finer, more persistent bubbles, higher acidity, and complex yeasty aromas from lees aging. Prosecco displays fruitier, more floral aromatics with softer acidity and less persistent bubbles due to the Charmat method. The texture difference is particularly noticeable – Champagne feels more creamy and structured, while Prosecco is lighter and more refreshing.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve Champagne and Prosecco at the same temperature?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Both should be served well-chilled at 42-45°F (6-7°C), but Prosecco benefits from being served slightly colder due to its lighter style and higher residual sugar in many examples. Champagne can handle being served at the warmer end of this range to better showcase its complexity. Use narrow flutes for both to preserve bubbles, though Champagne also works beautifully in white wine glasses to enhance aromatics.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can you store opened Champagne vs Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Champagne typically maintains its quality 3-5 days after opening when properly sealed and refrigerated, thanks to its higher acidity and more robust structure from traditional method production. Prosecco should ideally be consumed within 1-3 days of opening, as its lighter style and Charmat method production make it less resilient to oxidation. Both benefit from proper sparkling wine stoppers that maintain pressure better than regular cork stoppers.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing between Champagne and Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is assuming all Prosecco is sweet and simple, or that expensive Champagne is always superior for every occasion. Many Proseccos, especially from Valdobbiadene and Cartizze, are bone-dry and remarkably sophisticated. Conversely, mass-market Champagne can be less interesting than premium Prosecco. Focus on the specific producer and style rather than just the category name.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Prosecco or Champagne better for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Prosecco is generally more approachable for beginners due to its softer acidity, fruitier flavor profile, and lower price point for experimentation. Its peachy, apple, and floral notes are immediately appealing, while Champagne's mineral complexity and austere character can seem challenging initially. However, starting with a well-made Brut Champagne from a major house like Moët or Veuve Clicquot provides an excellent introduction to traditional method sparkling wines.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good alternatives that split the difference between Champagne and Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Crémant wines from France offer excellent middle-ground options, using Champagne's traditional method but from regions like Loire or Burgundy, typically priced between Prosecco and Champagne. Spanish Cava, particularly from premium producers like Gramona or Recaredo, provides traditional method complexity at moderate prices. English sparkling wine increasingly offers Champagne-style elegance, while high-end Franciacorta from Italy delivers sophisticated traditional method wines with Italian character.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which pairs better with food: Champagne or Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Champagne's higher acidity and more complex flavor structure make it superior for rich foods like oysters, caviar, aged cheeses, and cream-based dishes. Prosecco excels with lighter fare like fresh seafood, salads, fruit-based desserts, and spicy Asian cuisine where its softer profile won't compete. However, both work wonderfully as aperitifs, and the choice often depends more on the specific wine's dryness level and the occasion's formality than the category alone.</p>
  </div>
